{
  "texts": [
    "The use of the elemental compositions of feedstocks does not require complicated multi-step procedures found in a direct biochemical composition analysis.",
    "First, a total of 268 data points of elemental compositions were gathered from the literature, with details outlined in Supplementary Data and Supplementary Note 6.",
    "We then made the assumption, which is considered reasonable, that within each type of waste, carbon (C), hydrogen (H), oxygen (O), and nitrogen (N) contribute to carbohydrates, proteins, lipids, and lignin (Supplementary Note 5).",
    "An optimization problem (Section ''Feed Composition Analysis'') was formulated and solved for each data point with respect to the elemental balances to estimate the mass fractions of the key biochemical components that best fit the ultimate analysis data (Fig. 2a).",
    "Each data point is assigned a weight based on its category, following the statistics of waste streams studied by EPA 32."
  ]
}